Jane Sloman (b. Ipswich, 15 December 1824, d. after 1850) was an English composer, pianist, and vocalist, who had an active concert career in the United States during the 1840s.
In 1839, she moved to the United States as one of the only female piano virtuosos in the country.
Sloman’s debut was held at Niblo's Gardens in New York on 16 July 1841, when she was seventeen.
She was among the first generation of professional women composers that emerged in the 1850s including Augusta Browne, Marion Dix Sullivan, Faustina Hodges, and Susan Parkhurst.
Her last known concert took place on February 18, 1850.
Her compositions were published under the name Sloman Torry after 1862.
While her last public appearance as a pianist occurred in 1850, her songs and compositions continued to be published until 1902, speaking to their lingering popularity.
